&lt;p&gt;The correct answer is &lt;u&gt;&lt;strong&gt;Huygens&amp;#39; Principle&lt;/strong&gt;&lt;/u&gt;.&lt;/p&gt;

&lt;p&gt;&lt;span style=&quot;display: flex;gap: 6px;align-items: center;&quot;&gt;&lt;img height=&quot;26px&quot; src=&quot;//cdn.testbook.com/resources/lms_creative_elements/key-point-image.png&quot; width=&quot;26px&quot; /&gt;&lt;strong&gt;&lt;span style=&quot;vertical-align: middle;font-size: 21px;&quot;&gt;&lt;u&gt;Key Points&lt;/u&gt;&lt;/span&gt;&lt;/strong&gt;&lt;/span&gt;&lt;/p&gt;

&lt;ul&gt;
	&lt;li&gt;&lt;strong&gt;Huygens&amp;#39; Principle&lt;/strong&gt; states that every point on a wavefront acts as a source of secondary wavelets, which spread out in all directions at the same speed as the wave. The new wavefront is formed by the envelope of these secondary wavelets.&lt;/li&gt;
	&lt;li&gt;This principle was proposed by &lt;strong&gt;Christiaan Huygens&lt;/strong&gt; in &lt;strong&gt;1690&lt;/strong&gt; and serves as a foundational concept in wave theory and optics.&lt;/li&gt;
	&lt;li&gt;Huygens&amp;#39; Principle is fundamental to understanding phenomena like &lt;strong&gt;reflection, refraction, diffraction, and interference&lt;/strong&gt; of waves.&lt;/li&gt;
	&lt;li&gt;The principle applies to all types of waves, including &lt;strong&gt;light waves, sound waves, and water waves&lt;/strong&gt;, making it a universal concept in wave mechanics.&lt;/li&gt;
	&lt;li&gt;It provides a clear explanation of the behavior of light as a wave, particularly when passing through media or around obstacles.&lt;/li&gt;
&lt;/ul&gt;

&lt;p&gt;&lt;span style=&quot;display: flex;gap: 6px;align-items: center;&quot;&gt;&lt;img height=&quot;26px&quot; src=&quot;//cdn.testbook.com/resources/lms_creative_elements/additional-information-image.png&quot; width=&quot;26px&quot; /&gt;&lt;strong&gt;&lt;span style=&quot;vertical-align: middle;font-size: 21px;&quot;&gt;&lt;u&gt;Additional Information&lt;/u&gt;&lt;/span&gt;&lt;/strong&gt;&lt;/span&gt;&lt;/p&gt;

&lt;ul&gt;
	&lt;li&gt;&lt;strong&gt;Doppler&amp;#39;s Principle:&lt;/strong&gt;

	&lt;ul&gt;
		&lt;li&gt;Doppler&amp;#39;s Principle, or Doppler Effect, explains the change in frequency or wavelength of a wave in relation to an observer moving relative to the wave source.&lt;/li&gt;
		&lt;li&gt;It is commonly observed in sound waves and light waves, such as the change in pitch of a siren as it moves closer or farther away.&lt;/li&gt;
		&lt;li&gt;This principle is widely used in applications like weather radar, astronomical observations, and medical imaging.&lt;/li&gt;
	&lt;/ul&gt;
	&lt;/li&gt;
	&lt;li&gt;&lt;strong&gt;Fermat&amp;#39;s Principle:&lt;/strong&gt;
	&lt;ul&gt;
		&lt;li&gt;Fermat&amp;#39;s Principle states that light follows the path that takes the least time when traveling from one point to another.&lt;/li&gt;
		&lt;li&gt;It is a fundamental concept in geometrical optics and explains the behavior of light in phenomena like reflection and refraction.&lt;/li&gt;
		&lt;li&gt;This principle is named after the French mathematician &lt;strong&gt;Pierre de Fermat&lt;/strong&gt;.&lt;/li&gt;
	&lt;/ul&gt;
	&lt;/li&gt;
	&lt;li&gt;&lt;strong&gt;Superposition Principle:&lt;/strong&gt;
	&lt;ul&gt;
		&lt;li&gt;The Superposition Principle states that when two or more waves overlap, the resulting wave is the sum of the individual waves.&lt;/li&gt;
		&lt;li&gt;This principle is key to understanding interference patterns and is applicable to all types of waves, including sound, light, and water waves.&lt;/li&gt;
		&lt;li&gt;It explains phenomena such as constructive and destructive interference.&lt;/li&gt;
	&lt;/ul&gt;
	&lt;/li&gt;
	&lt;li&gt;&lt;strong&gt;Applications of Huygens&amp;#39; Principle:&lt;/strong&gt;
	&lt;ul&gt;
		&lt;li&gt;Huygens&amp;#39; Principle is used to derive laws of reflection and refraction.&lt;/li&gt;
		&lt;li&gt;It helps explain the bending of light around obstacles, a phenomenon known as diffraction.&lt;/li&gt;
		&lt;li&gt;The principle aids in understanding interference patterns, such as those observed in double-slit experiments.&lt;/li&gt;
		&lt;li&gt;It is crucial in designing optical instruments like microscopes and telescopes.&lt;/li&gt;
	&lt;/ul&gt;
	&lt;/li&gt;
&lt;/ul&gt;

&lt;p&gt;&lt;span style=&quot;display: flex;gap: 6px;align-items: center;&quot;&gt;&lt;img height=&quot;26px&quot; src=&quot;//cdn.testbook.com/resources/lms_creative_elements/important-point-image.png&quot; width=&quot;26px&quot; /&gt;&lt;strong&gt;&lt;span style=&quot;vertical-align: middle;font-size: 21px;&quot;&gt;&lt;u&gt;Important Points&lt;/u&gt;&lt;/span&gt;&lt;/strong&gt;&lt;/span&gt;&lt;/p&gt;

&lt;ul&gt;
	&lt;li&gt;&lt;strong&gt;Historical Background:&lt;/strong&gt;

	&lt;ul&gt;
		&lt;li&gt;Huygens&amp;#39; Principle was instrumental in the development of the wave theory of light, which later paved the way for modern optics.&lt;/li&gt;
		&lt;li&gt;It was challenged by Newton&amp;#39;s corpuscular theory but eventually gained acceptance due to its ability to explain phenomena like diffraction and interference.&lt;/li&gt;
	&lt;/ul&gt;
	&lt;/li&gt;
	&lt;li&gt;&lt;strong&gt;Modern Implications:&lt;/strong&gt;
	&lt;ul&gt;
		&lt;li&gt;The principle is used in computational methods like the finite-difference time-domain (FDTD) method for solving wave equations.&lt;/li&gt;
		&lt;li&gt;It plays a critical role in fields such as acoustics, optics, and electromagnetism.&lt;/li&gt;
	&lt;/ul&gt;
	&lt;/li&gt;
&lt;/ul&gt;

&lt;p&gt;The correct answer is &lt;u&gt;&lt;strong&gt;Joule&lt;/strong&gt;&lt;/u&gt;.&lt;/p&gt;

&lt;p&gt;&lt;span style=&quot;display: flex;gap: 6px;align-items: center;&quot;&gt;&lt;img height=&quot;26px&quot; src=&quot;//cdn.testbook.com/resources/lms_creative_elements/key-point-image.png&quot; width=&quot;26px&quot; /&gt;&lt;u style=&quot;font-size: 21px; font-weight: bolder; font-family: var(--bs-body-font-family); text-align: var(--bs-body-text-align);&quot;&gt;Key Points&lt;/u&gt;&lt;/span&gt;&lt;/p&gt;

&lt;ul&gt;
	&lt;li&gt;The SI (International System of Units) unit of energy is the &lt;strong&gt;Joule (symbol: J)&lt;/strong&gt;.&lt;/li&gt;
	&lt;li&gt;One Joule is defined as the &lt;strong&gt;energy transferred&lt;/strong&gt; when a force of one newton moves an object by one meter.&lt;/li&gt;
	&lt;li&gt;The Joule is named after the physicist &lt;strong&gt;James Prescott Joule&lt;/strong&gt;, who contributed significantly to the study of energy.&lt;/li&gt;
	&lt;li&gt;1 Joule is equivalent to &lt;strong&gt;1 Newton-meter (N&amp;middot;m)&lt;/strong&gt; or &lt;strong&gt;1 kg&amp;middot;m&amp;sup2;/s&amp;sup2;&lt;/strong&gt; in base SI units.&lt;/li&gt;
	&lt;li&gt;Joule is used to measure various forms of energy, including &lt;strong&gt;kinetic energy, potential energy, thermal energy, and electrical energy&lt;/strong&gt;.&lt;/li&gt;
&lt;/ul&gt;

&lt;p&gt;&lt;span style=&quot;display: flex;gap: 6px;align-items: center;&quot;&gt;&lt;img height=&quot;26px&quot; src=&quot;//cdn.testbook.com/resources/lms_creative_elements/additional-information-image.png&quot; width=&quot;26px&quot; /&gt;&lt;strong&gt;&lt;span style=&quot;vertical-align: middle;font-size: 21px;&quot;&gt;&lt;u&gt;Additional Information&lt;/u&gt;&lt;/span&gt;&lt;/strong&gt;&lt;/span&gt;&lt;/p&gt;

&lt;ul&gt;
	&lt;li&gt;&lt;strong&gt;Watt&lt;/strong&gt;:

	&lt;ul&gt;
		&lt;li&gt;Watt (W) is the SI unit of power, not energy.&lt;/li&gt;
		&lt;li&gt;1 Watt is defined as 1 Joule per second (1 W = 1 J/s).&lt;/li&gt;
	&lt;/ul&gt;
	&lt;/li&gt;
	&lt;li&gt;&lt;strong&gt;Kelvin&lt;/strong&gt;:
	&lt;ul&gt;
		&lt;li&gt;Kelvin (K) is the SI unit of temperature, not energy.&lt;/li&gt;
		&lt;li&gt;It is used to measure the thermodynamic temperature scale.&lt;/li&gt;
	&lt;/ul&gt;
	&lt;/li&gt;
	&lt;li&gt;&lt;strong&gt;Newton&lt;/strong&gt;:
	&lt;ul&gt;
		&lt;li&gt;Newton (N) is the SI unit of force, not energy.&lt;/li&gt;
		&lt;li&gt;1 Newton is the force required to accelerate a 1 kg mass by 1 meter per second squared (1 N = 1 kg&amp;middot;m/s&amp;sup2;).&lt;/li&gt;
	&lt;/ul&gt;
	&lt;/li&gt;
	&lt;li&gt;&lt;strong&gt;Relationship Between Energy and Work&lt;/strong&gt;:
	&lt;ul&gt;
		&lt;li&gt;Energy is the capacity to do work, and work is the transfer of energy.&lt;/li&gt;
		&lt;li&gt;Both energy and work are measured in Joules.&lt;/li&gt;
	&lt;/ul&gt;
	&lt;/li&gt;
	&lt;li&gt;&lt;strong&gt;Other Common Units of Energy&lt;/strong&gt;:
	&lt;ul&gt;
		&lt;li&gt;Calorie (cal): Commonly used in food energy, 1 cal = 4.184 Joules.&lt;/li&gt;
		&lt;li&gt;Electronvolt (eV): Used in atomic and particle physics, 1 eV = 1.602 &amp;times; 10⁻&amp;sup1;⁹ Joules.&lt;/li&gt;
	&lt;/ul&gt;
	&lt;/li&gt;
&lt;/ul&gt;

&lt;p data-end=&quot;57&quot; data-start=&quot;0&quot;&gt;The correct answer is &lt;u&gt;&lt;strong&gt;Sonar&lt;/strong&gt;&lt;/u&gt;.&lt;/p&gt;

&lt;p data-end=&quot;57&quot; data-start=&quot;0&quot;&gt;&lt;span style=&quot;display: flex;gap: 6px;align-items: center;&quot;&gt;&lt;img height=&quot;26px&quot; src=&quot;//cdn.testbook.com/resources/lms_creative_elements/key-point-image.png&quot; width=&quot;26px&quot; /&gt;&lt;strong&gt;&lt;span style=&quot;vertical-align: middle;font-size: 21px;&quot;&gt;&lt;u&gt;Key Points&lt;/u&gt;&lt;/span&gt;&lt;/strong&gt;&lt;/span&gt;&lt;/p&gt;

&lt;ul&gt;
	&lt;li data-end=&quot;284&quot; data-start=&quot;78&quot;&gt;&lt;strong&gt;Sonar&lt;/strong&gt; (Sound Navigation and Ranging) is a technology that uses &lt;strong&gt;sound waves&lt;/strong&gt; to detect, locate, and map objects underwater. It operates by emitting sound pulses and measuring the time taken for the echo to return after bouncing off an object.&lt;/li&gt;
	&lt;li data-end=&quot;605&quot; data-start=&quot;482&quot;&gt;&lt;strong&gt;Acoustic waves&lt;/strong&gt; are the core component of sonar technology. These waves travel through water, hit an object, and reflect back, allowing the system to calculate the object&amp;rsquo;s location based on the time and speed of sound.&lt;/li&gt;
	&lt;li data-end=&quot;692&quot; data-start=&quot;610&quot;&gt;Sonar is widely used for &lt;strong&gt;navigating, mapping the ocean floor, detecting submerged objects like submarines, and conducting scientific research&lt;/strong&gt;.&lt;/li&gt;
	&lt;li data-end=&quot;1041&quot; data-start=&quot;850&quot;&gt;It is especially useful in &lt;strong&gt;marine environments&lt;/strong&gt;, where visibility is low, and other technologies like radar do not function effectively underwater due to the attenuation of electromagnetic waves.&lt;/li&gt;
	&lt;li data-end=&quot;1162&quot; data-start=&quot;1046&quot;&gt;Sonar systems are classified into two types: &lt;strong&gt;active sonar&lt;/strong&gt; (which emits sound waves and listens for echoes) and &lt;strong&gt;passive sonar&lt;/strong&gt; (which only listens for sounds made by other objects). Both play vital roles in underwater navigation and exploration.&lt;/li&gt;
	&lt;li data-end=&quot;1560&quot; data-start=&quot;1323&quot;&gt;The applications of sonar include &lt;strong&gt;military purposes&lt;/strong&gt; (submarine detection, mine hunting), &lt;strong&gt;commercial uses&lt;/strong&gt; (fish finding, underwater oil exploration), and &lt;strong&gt;scientific research&lt;/strong&gt; (mapping oceanic structures).&lt;/li&gt;
	&lt;li data-end=&quot;1654&quot; data-start=&quot;1565&quot;&gt;&lt;em&gt;&lt;strong&gt;Hence, the correct answer is &lt;span style=&quot;color: rgb(33, 37, 41);&quot;&gt;Sonar&lt;/span&gt;.&lt;/strong&gt;&lt;/em&gt;&lt;/li&gt;
&lt;/ul&gt;

&lt;p&gt;&lt;span style=&quot;display: flex;gap: 6px;align-items: center;&quot;&gt;&lt;img height=&quot;26px&quot; src=&quot;//cdn.testbook.com/resources/lms_creative_elements/additional-information-image.png&quot; width=&quot;26px&quot; /&gt;&lt;strong&gt;&lt;span style=&quot;vertical-align: middle;font-size: 21px;&quot;&gt;&lt;u&gt;Additional Information&lt;/u&gt;&lt;/span&gt;&lt;/strong&gt;&lt;/span&gt;&lt;/p&gt;

&lt;ul&gt;
	&lt;li&gt;&lt;strong&gt;Technologies Mentioned in the Question:&lt;/strong&gt;

	&lt;ul&gt;
		&lt;li data-end=&quot;2410&quot; data-start=&quot;2195&quot;&gt;&lt;strong&gt;Sonar:&lt;/strong&gt; Used for underwater exploration, navigation, and object detection. It is highly effective in water where visibility is limited. Applications include military submarines, undersea exploration, and commercial fishing.&lt;/li&gt;
		&lt;li data-end=&quot;2684&quot; data-start=&quot;2415&quot;&gt;&lt;strong&gt;LiDAR:&lt;/strong&gt; (Light Detection and Ranging) uses &lt;strong&gt;laser light&lt;/strong&gt; to measure distances. It is primarily used for mapping and surveying land-based terrains, not underwater applications, as light cannot penetrate water efficiently.&lt;/li&gt;
		&lt;li data-end=&quot;2860&quot; data-start=&quot;2735&quot;&gt;&lt;strong&gt;Echo-sounder:&lt;/strong&gt; A specialized form of sonar used in marine environments to measure the depth of water and locate the seabed. It is commonly used in hydrographic surveys.&lt;/li&gt;
		&lt;li data-end=&quot;3071&quot; data-start=&quot;2865&quot;&gt;&lt;strong&gt;SAR:&lt;/strong&gt; (Synthetic Aperture Radar) uses microwave radar technology to create two-dimensional images of objects, such as landscapes or buildings. It is not suitable for underwater object detection.&lt;/li&gt;
	&lt;/ul&gt;
	&lt;/li&gt;
	&lt;li&gt;&lt;strong&gt;Sonar in Detail:&lt;/strong&gt;
	&lt;ul&gt;
		&lt;li data-end=&quot;3250&quot; data-start=&quot;3076&quot;&gt;&lt;strong&gt;Active Sonar:&lt;/strong&gt; Emits sound waves and analyzes the echo for distance, size, and shape of the object. Used in military applications like submarine tracking and anti-mine operations.&lt;/li&gt;
		&lt;li data-end=&quot;3402&quot; data-start=&quot;3301&quot;&gt;&lt;strong&gt;Passive Sonar:&lt;/strong&gt; Only listens to sounds generated by underwater objects. Widely used in detecting marine life, ships, and submarines.&lt;/li&gt;
		&lt;li data-end=&quot;3580&quot; data-start=&quot;3407&quot;&gt;&lt;strong&gt;Key Applications:&lt;/strong&gt; Includes ocean floor mapping, fish population tracking, underwater archaeology, and disaster management (e.g., detecting underwater earthquakes).&lt;/li&gt;
	&lt;/ul&gt;
	&lt;/li&gt;
	&lt;li&gt;&lt;strong&gt;Important Characteristics:&lt;/strong&gt;
	&lt;ul&gt;
		&lt;li data-end=&quot;3729&quot; data-start=&quot;3585&quot;&gt;Sonar technology is reliable in underwater environments due to the efficient propagation of sound waves in water compared to electromagnetic waves (used in radar).&lt;/li&gt;
		&lt;li data-end=&quot;3865&quot; data-start=&quot;3734&quot;&gt;The speed of sound in water is approximately &lt;strong&gt;1500 meters per second&lt;/strong&gt;, allowing accurate calculations of object distance and location.&lt;/li&gt;
	&lt;/ul&gt;
	&lt;/li&gt;
&lt;/ul&gt;

&lt;p&gt;&lt;span style=&quot;display: flex;gap: 6px;align-items: center;&quot;&gt;&lt;img height=&quot;26px&quot; src=&quot;//cdn.testbook.com/resources/lms_creative_elements/important-point-image.png&quot; width=&quot;26px&quot; /&gt;&lt;strong&gt;&lt;span style=&quot;vertical-align: middle;font-size: 21px;&quot;&gt;&lt;u&gt;Important Points&lt;/u&gt;&lt;/span&gt;&lt;/strong&gt;&lt;/span&gt;&lt;/p&gt;

&lt;ul&gt;
	&lt;li&gt;&lt;strong&gt;Key Advantages of Sonar:&lt;/strong&gt;

	&lt;ul&gt;
		&lt;li data-end=&quot;4636&quot; data-start=&quot;4411&quot;&gt;Sonar is effective in environments where visibility is limited, such as deep-sea exploration or murky waters.&lt;/li&gt;
		&lt;li data-end=&quot;4761&quot; data-start=&quot;4641&quot;&gt;It can detect both stationary and moving objects, making it versatile for different applications.&lt;/li&gt;
	&lt;/ul&gt;
	&lt;/li&gt;
	&lt;li&gt;&lt;strong&gt;Limitations of Sonar:&lt;/strong&gt;
	&lt;ul&gt;
		&lt;li data-end=&quot;5043&quot; data-start=&quot;4817&quot;&gt;The accuracy of sonar can be affected by water conditions such as temperature, salinity, and pressure.&lt;/li&gt;
		&lt;li data-end=&quot;5259&quot; data-start=&quot;5048&quot;&gt;Sonar systems can face interference from marine life or other sound sources in the water.&lt;/li&gt;
	&lt;/ul&gt;
	&lt;/li&gt;
&lt;/ul&gt;

&lt;p&gt;The correct answer is &lt;u&gt;&lt;strong&gt;Kolbe&amp;rsquo;s reaction&lt;/strong&gt;&lt;/u&gt;.&lt;/p&gt;

&lt;p&gt;&lt;span style=&quot;display: flex;gap: 6px;align-items: center;&quot;&gt;&lt;img height=&quot;26px&quot; src=&quot;//cdn.testbook.com/resources/lms_creative_elements/key-point-image.png&quot; width=&quot;26px&quot; /&gt;&lt;strong&gt;&lt;span style=&quot;vertical-align: middle;font-size: 21px;&quot;&gt;&lt;u&gt;Key Points&lt;/u&gt;&lt;/span&gt;&lt;/strong&gt;&lt;/span&gt;&lt;/p&gt;

&lt;ul style=&quot;color: (33, 37, 41);&quot;&gt;
	&lt;li&gt;&lt;strong&gt;Kolbe&amp;rsquo;s reaction&lt;/strong&gt; is a chemical process that is primarily used to synthesize &lt;strong&gt;salicylic acid&lt;/strong&gt;, also known as &lt;strong&gt;ortho-hydroxybenzoic acid.&lt;/strong&gt;&lt;/li&gt;
	&lt;li&gt;This reaction involves the &lt;strong&gt;carboxylation of phenolates&lt;/strong&gt; (sodium phenoxide) with &lt;strong&gt;carbon dioxide&lt;/strong&gt; under high pressure and moderate temperature.&lt;/li&gt;
	&lt;li&gt;The reaction is widely used in the &lt;strong&gt;pharmaceutical industry&lt;/strong&gt; for the production of &lt;strong&gt;salicylic acid&lt;/strong&gt;, which serves as a precursor for &lt;strong&gt;medications like aspirin.&lt;/strong&gt;&lt;/li&gt;
	&lt;li&gt;In this reaction, sodium phenoxide reacts with &lt;strong&gt;CO&lt;sub&gt;2&lt;/sub&gt;&lt;/strong&gt; to form sodium salicylate, which is then acidified to yield salicylic acid.&lt;/li&gt;
	&lt;li&gt;It demonstrates the practical application of &lt;strong&gt;organic synthesis&lt;/strong&gt; in creating an essential compound for drug manufacturing.&lt;/li&gt;
	&lt;li&gt;This reaction is &lt;strong&gt;cost-effective&lt;/strong&gt; and a preferred method for producing ortho-hydroxybenzoic acid on an industrial scale.&lt;/li&gt;
&lt;/ul&gt;

&lt;p&gt;&lt;span style=&quot;display: flex;gap: 6px;align-items: center;&quot;&gt;&lt;img height=&quot;26px&quot; src=&quot;//cdn.testbook.com/resources/lms_creative_elements/additional-information-image.png&quot; width=&quot;26px&quot; /&gt; &lt;strong&gt;&lt;span style=&quot;vertical-align: middle;font-size: 21px;&quot;&gt;&lt;u&gt;Additional Information&lt;/u&gt;&lt;/span&gt;&lt;/strong&gt;&lt;/span&gt;&lt;/p&gt;

&lt;ul&gt;
	&lt;li&gt;&lt;u&gt;&lt;strong&gt;Stephen reaction&lt;/strong&gt;&lt;/u&gt;

	&lt;ul&gt;
		&lt;li&gt;The &lt;strong&gt;Stephen reaction&lt;/strong&gt; is used to synthesize &lt;strong&gt;aldehydes&lt;/strong&gt; from nitriles by reducing them with &lt;strong&gt;tin chloride (SnCl&lt;sub&gt;2&lt;/sub&gt;)&lt;/strong&gt; and hydrochloric acid.&lt;/li&gt;
		&lt;li&gt;This reaction is not related to the production of ortho-hydroxybenzoic acid.&lt;/li&gt;
		&lt;li&gt;It is primarily utilized in the synthesis of simple aldehydes in organic chemistry.&lt;/li&gt;
	&lt;/ul&gt;
	&lt;/li&gt;
	&lt;li&gt;&lt;u&gt;&lt;strong&gt;Reimer-Tiemann reaction&lt;/strong&gt;&lt;/u&gt;
	&lt;ul&gt;
		&lt;li&gt;The &lt;strong&gt;Reimer-Tiemann reaction&lt;/strong&gt; is used to synthesize &lt;strong&gt;ortho-hydroxybenzaldehyde&lt;/strong&gt;, not ortho-hydroxybenzoic acid.&lt;/li&gt;
		&lt;li&gt;It involves the reaction of phenol with &lt;strong&gt;chloroform (CHCl&lt;sub&gt;3&lt;/sub&gt;)&lt;/strong&gt; in the presence of a strong base, such as &lt;strong&gt;sodium hydroxide.&lt;/strong&gt;&lt;/li&gt;
		&lt;li&gt;The reaction is specifically used in the preparation of aromatic aldehydes.&lt;/li&gt;
	&lt;/ul&gt;
	&lt;/li&gt;
	&lt;li&gt;&lt;u&gt;&lt;strong&gt;Friedel-Crafts reaction&lt;/strong&gt;&lt;/u&gt;
	&lt;ul&gt;
		&lt;li&gt;The &lt;strong&gt;Friedel-Crafts reaction&lt;/strong&gt; is used for the &lt;strong&gt;alkylation or acylation of aromatic compounds&lt;/strong&gt; using a Lewis acid catalyst such as &lt;strong&gt;AlCl&lt;sub&gt;3&lt;/sub&gt;&lt;/strong&gt;.&lt;/li&gt;
		&lt;li&gt;This reaction is not applicable for the synthesis of ortho-hydroxybenzoic acid.&lt;/li&gt;
		&lt;li&gt;It is commonly used in organic chemistry to create aromatic ketones and hydrocarbons.&lt;/li&gt;
	&lt;/ul&gt;
	&lt;/li&gt;
&lt;/ul&gt;

&lt;p&gt;The correct answer is &lt;u&gt;&lt;strong&gt;100 Hz&lt;/strong&gt;&lt;/u&gt;.&lt;/p&gt;

&lt;p&gt;&lt;span style=&quot;display: flex;gap: 6px;align-items: center;&quot;&gt;&lt;img height=&quot;26px&quot; src=&quot;//cdn.testbook.com/resources/lms_creative_elements/key-point-image.png&quot; width=&quot;26px&quot; /&gt;&lt;u style=&quot;font-size: 21px; font-weight: bolder; font-family: var(--bs-body-font-family); text-align: var(--bs-body-text-align);&quot;&gt;Key Points&lt;/u&gt;&lt;/span&gt;&lt;/p&gt;

&lt;ul&gt;
	&lt;li&gt;The relationship between frequency and period is defined as &lt;strong&gt;Frequency = 1 / Period&lt;/strong&gt;.&lt;/li&gt;
	&lt;li&gt;A sound wave with a period of 0.01 seconds has a frequency calculated as &lt;strong&gt;1 / 0.01 = 100 Hz&lt;/strong&gt;.&lt;/li&gt;
	&lt;li&gt;Frequency is measured in &lt;strong&gt;Hertz (Hz)&lt;/strong&gt;, which represents the number of cycles per second.&lt;/li&gt;
	&lt;li&gt;Sound waves with a frequency of 100 Hz fall within the range of &lt;strong&gt;human hearing, typically between 20 Hz to 20,000 Hz.&lt;/strong&gt;&lt;/li&gt;
	&lt;li&gt;The period and frequency are inversely related&amp;mdash;if the period is short, the frequency is high, and vice versa.&lt;/li&gt;
&lt;/ul&gt;

&lt;p&gt;&lt;span style=&quot;display: flex;gap: 6px;align-items: center;&quot;&gt;&lt;img height=&quot;26px&quot; src=&quot;//cdn.testbook.com/resources/lms_creative_elements/additional-information-image.png&quot; width=&quot;26px&quot; /&gt;&lt;strong&gt;&lt;span style=&quot;vertical-align: middle;font-size: 21px;&quot;&gt;&lt;u&gt;Additional Information&lt;/u&gt;&lt;/span&gt;&lt;/strong&gt;&lt;/span&gt;&lt;/p&gt;

&lt;ul&gt;
	&lt;li&gt;&lt;strong&gt;Frequency:&lt;/strong&gt;

	&lt;ul&gt;
		&lt;li&gt;Frequency refers to the number of oscillations or cycles a wave completes in one second.&lt;/li&gt;
		&lt;li&gt;It is measured in Hertz (Hz), where 1 Hz equals one cycle per second.&lt;/li&gt;
	&lt;/ul&gt;
	&lt;/li&gt;
	&lt;li&gt;&lt;strong&gt;Period:&lt;/strong&gt;
	&lt;ul&gt;
		&lt;li&gt;The period is the time taken for one complete cycle of a wave.&lt;/li&gt;
		&lt;li&gt;It is expressed in seconds and is the reciprocal of frequency.&lt;/li&gt;
	&lt;/ul&gt;
	&lt;/li&gt;
	&lt;li&gt;&lt;strong&gt;Sound Waves:&lt;/strong&gt;
	&lt;ul&gt;
		&lt;li&gt;Sound waves are longitudinal waves that travel through a medium (air, water, solids).&lt;/li&gt;
		&lt;li&gt;They consist of compressions and rarefactions caused by vibrating objects.&lt;/li&gt;
	&lt;/ul&gt;
	&lt;/li&gt;
	&lt;li&gt;&lt;strong&gt;Human Hearing Range:&lt;/strong&gt;
	&lt;ul&gt;
		&lt;li&gt;Humans can typically hear frequencies ranging from 20 Hz to 20,000 Hz.&lt;/li&gt;
		&lt;li&gt;Frequencies below 20 Hz are called infrasonic, and frequencies above 20,000 Hz are ultrasonic.&lt;/li&gt;
	&lt;/ul&gt;
	&lt;/li&gt;
&lt;/ul&gt;

&lt;p&gt;The correct answer is &lt;u&gt;&lt;strong&gt;[ML&lt;sup&gt;-1&lt;/sup&gt;T&lt;sup&gt;-2&lt;/sup&gt;]&lt;/strong&gt;&lt;/u&gt;.&lt;/p&gt;

&lt;p&gt;&lt;span style=&quot;display: flex;gap: 6px;align-items: center;&quot;&gt;&lt;img height=&quot;26px&quot; src=&quot;//cdn.testbook.com/resources/lms_creative_elements/key-point-image.png&quot; width=&quot;26px&quot; /&gt;&lt;strong&gt;&lt;span style=&quot;vertical-align: middle;font-size: 21px;&quot;&gt;&lt;u&gt;Key Points&lt;/u&gt;&lt;/span&gt;&lt;/strong&gt;&lt;/span&gt;&lt;/p&gt;

&lt;ul style=&quot;color: (33, 37, 41);&quot;&gt;
	&lt;li&gt;&lt;strong&gt;Pressure&lt;/strong&gt; is defined as the &lt;strong&gt;force&lt;/strong&gt; applied per unit &lt;strong&gt;area&lt;/strong&gt;.&lt;/li&gt;
	&lt;li&gt;Mathematically, &lt;strong&gt;Pressure = Force / Area&lt;/strong&gt;.&lt;/li&gt;
	&lt;li&gt;&lt;strong&gt;Force&lt;/strong&gt; has the dimensional formula &lt;strong&gt;[MLT&lt;sup&gt;-2&lt;/sup&gt;]&lt;/strong&gt;, where M = mass, L = length, T = time.&lt;/li&gt;
	&lt;li&gt;&lt;strong&gt;Area&lt;/strong&gt; has the dimensional formula &lt;strong&gt;[L2]&lt;/strong&gt;.&lt;/li&gt;
	&lt;li&gt;Dividing force by area gives &lt;strong&gt;[MLT&lt;sup&gt;-2&lt;/sup&gt;] / [L&lt;sup&gt;2&lt;/sup&gt;] = [ML&lt;sup&gt;-1&lt;/sup&gt;T&lt;sup&gt;-2&lt;/sup&gt;]&lt;/strong&gt;, which is the dimensional formula of pressure.&lt;/li&gt;
	&lt;li&gt;&lt;strong&gt;Applications:&lt;/strong&gt; Pressure is used in fields like &lt;strong&gt;fluid mechanics, hydraulics, meteorology, and engineering design&lt;/strong&gt;.&lt;/li&gt;
	&lt;li&gt;&lt;strong&gt;Examples:&lt;/strong&gt; Atmospheric pressure, blood pressure, and pressure in hydraulic lifts.&lt;/li&gt;
&lt;/ul&gt;

&lt;p&gt;&lt;span style=&quot;display: flex;gap: 6px;align-items: center;&quot;&gt;&lt;img height=&quot;26px&quot; src=&quot;//cdn.testbook.com/resources/lms_creative_elements/additional-information-image.png&quot; width=&quot;26px&quot; /&gt; &lt;strong&gt;&lt;span style=&quot;vertical-align: middle;font-size: 21px;&quot;&gt;&lt;u&gt;Additional Information&lt;/u&gt;&lt;/span&gt;&lt;/strong&gt;&lt;/span&gt;&lt;/p&gt;

&lt;ul&gt;
	&lt;li&gt;&lt;u&gt;&lt;strong&gt;[ML&lt;sup&gt;-2&lt;/sup&gt;T&lt;sup&gt;-2&lt;/sup&gt;]&lt;/strong&gt;&lt;/u&gt;: This dimensional formula corresponds to &lt;strong&gt;surface tension&lt;/strong&gt;.

	&lt;ul&gt;
		&lt;li&gt;&lt;strong&gt;Surface tension&lt;/strong&gt; represents force per unit &lt;strong&gt;length&lt;/strong&gt; along the surface of a liquid.&lt;/li&gt;
		&lt;li&gt;Common applications include &lt;strong&gt;capillary action, formation of droplets, and liquid interfaces in engineering.&lt;/strong&gt;&lt;/li&gt;
	&lt;/ul&gt;
	&lt;/li&gt;
	&lt;li&gt;&lt;u&gt;&lt;strong&gt;[ML&lt;sup&gt;2&lt;/sup&gt;T&lt;sup&gt;-2&lt;/sup&gt;]&lt;/strong&gt;&lt;/u&gt;:&amp;nbsp;This represents &lt;strong&gt;moment of force or torque&lt;/strong&gt;.
	&lt;ul&gt;
		&lt;li&gt;It is calculated as &lt;strong&gt;Force &amp;times; Distance&lt;/strong&gt; from the pivot.&lt;/li&gt;
		&lt;li&gt;Used in applications such as &lt;strong&gt;lever systems, mechanical rotation, and structural analysis.&lt;/strong&gt;&lt;/li&gt;
	&lt;/ul&gt;
	&lt;/li&gt;
	&lt;li&gt;&lt;u&gt;&lt;strong&gt;[MLT&lt;sup&gt;-2&lt;/sup&gt;]&lt;/strong&gt;&lt;/u&gt;:&amp;nbsp;This is the dimensional formula for force itself.
	&lt;ul&gt;
		&lt;li&gt;&lt;strong&gt;Force&lt;/strong&gt; acts on objects to produce &lt;strong&gt;acceleration&lt;/strong&gt;.&lt;/li&gt;
		&lt;li&gt;Applications include &lt;strong&gt;mechanics, dynamics, and structural design calculations.&lt;/strong&gt;&lt;/li&gt;
	&lt;/ul&gt;
	&lt;/li&gt;
&lt;/ul&gt;<br><br><p>সঠিক উত্তর হল <u><strong><span class="MathJax" data-mathml="<math xmlns="http://www.w3.org/1998/Math/MathML"><mo stretchy="false">[</mo><mi>M</mi><msup><mi>L</mi><mrow class="MJX-TeXAtom-ORD"><mo>&#x2212;</mo><mn>1</mn></mrow></msup><msup><mi>T</mi><mrow class="MJX-TeXAtom-ORD"><mo>&#x2212;</mo><mn>2</mn></mrow></msup><mo stretchy="false">]</mo></math>" id="MathJax-Element-12-Frame" role="presentation" style="position: relative;" tabindex="0"><nobr aria-hidden="true"><span class="math" id="MathJax-Span-142" style="width: 6.092em; display: inline-block;"><span style="display: inline-block; position: relative; width: 4.98em; height: 0px; font-size: 122%;"><span style="position: absolute; clip: rect(1.232em, 1004.86em, 2.638em, -999.997em); top: -2.222em; left: 0em;"><span class="mrow" id="MathJax-Span-143"><span class="mo" id="MathJax-Span-144" style="font-family: MathJax_Main;">[</span><span class="mi" id="MathJax-Span-145" style="font-family: MathJax_Math-italic;">M</span><span class="msubsup" id="MathJax-Span-146"><span style="display: inline-block; position: relative; width: 1.642em; height: 0px;"><span style="position: absolute; clip: rect(3.106em, 1000.65em, 4.16em, -999.997em); top: -3.978em; left: 0em;"><span class="mi" id="MathJax-Span-147" style="font-family: MathJax_Math-italic;">L</span></span><span style="position: absolute; top: -4.33em; left: 0.706em;"><span class="texatom" id="MathJax-Span-148"><span class="mrow" id="MathJax-Span-149"><span class="mo" id="MathJax-Span-150" style="font-size: 70.7%; font-family: MathJax_Main;">&minus;</span><span class="mn" id="MathJax-Span-151" style="font-size: 70.7%; font-family: MathJax_Main;">1</span></span></span></span></span></span><span class="msubsup" id="MathJax-Span-152"><span style="display: inline-block; position: relative; width: 1.759em; height: 0px;"><span style="position: absolute; clip: rect(3.106em, 1000.71em, 4.16em, -999.997em); top: -3.978em; left: 0em;"><span class="mi" id="MathJax-Span-153" style="font-family: MathJax_Math-italic;">T</span></span><span style="position: absolute; top: -4.33em; left: 0.764em;"><span class="texatom" id="MathJax-Span-154"><span class="mrow" id="MathJax-Span-155"><span class="mo" id="MathJax-Span-156" style="font-size: 70.7%; font-family: MathJax_Main;">&minus;</span><span class="mn" id="MathJax-Span-157" style="font-size: 70.7%; font-family: MathJax_Main;">2</span></span></span></span></span></span><span class="mo" id="MathJax-Span-158" style="font-family: MathJax_Main;">]</span></span></span></span></span></nobr><span class="MJX_Assistive_MathML" role="presentation"><math xmlns="http://www.w3.org/1998/Math/MathML"><mo stretchy="false">[</mo><mi>M</mi><msup><mi>L</mi><mrow class="MJX-TeXAtom-ORD"><mo>&minus;</mo><mn>1</mn></mrow></msup><msup><mi>T</mi><mrow class="MJX-TeXAtom-ORD"><mo>&minus;</mo><mn>2</mn></mrow></msup><mo stretchy="false">]</mo></math></span></span>
<script id="MathJax-Element-12" type="math/tex">[M L^{-1} T^{-2}]</script>
</strong></u>।</p>

<p><span style="display: flex;gap: 6px;align-items: center;"><img height="26px" src="//cdn.testbook.com/resources/lms_creative_elements/key-point-image.png" width="26px" /><u style="font-size: 21px; font-weight: bolder; font-family: var(--bs-body-font-family); text-align: var(--bs-body-text-align);">গুরুত্বপূর্ণ বিষয়</u></span></p>

<ul>
	<li>চাপকে প্রতি একক ক্ষেত্রফল হিসাবে সংজ্ঞায়িত করা হয়, গাণিতিকভাবে <span class="MathJax" data-mathml="<math xmlns="http://www.w3.org/1998/Math/MathML"><mi>P</mi><mo>=</mo><mfrac><mi>F</mi><mi>A</mi></mfrac></math>" id="MathJax-Element-13-Frame" role="presentation" style="position: relative;" tabindex="0"><nobr aria-hidden="true"><span class="math" id="MathJax-Span-159" style="width: 3.75em; display: inline-block;"><span style="display: inline-block; position: relative; width: 3.047em; height: 0px; font-size: 122%;"><span style="position: absolute; clip: rect(1.174em, 1003.05em, 2.813em, -999.997em); top: -2.222em; left: 0em;"><span class="mrow" id="MathJax-Span-160"><span class="mi" id="MathJax-Span-161" style="font-family: MathJax_Math-italic;">P</span><span class="mo" id="MathJax-Span-162" style="font-family: MathJax_Main; padding-left: 0.296em;">=</span><span class="mfrac" id="MathJax-Span-163" style="padding-left: 0.296em;"><span style="display: inline-block; position: relative; width: 0.647em; height: 0px; margin-right: 0.12em; margin-left: 0.12em;"><span style="position: absolute; clip: rect(3.34em, 1000.53em, 4.16em, -999.997em); top: -4.388em; left: 50%; margin-left: -0.29em;"><span class="mi" id="MathJax-Span-164" style="font-size: 70.7%; font-family: MathJax_Math-italic;">F</span></span><span style="position: absolute; clip: rect(3.282em, 1000.53em, 4.16em, -999.997em); top: -3.569em; left: 50%; margin-left: -0.29em;"><span class="mi" id="MathJax-Span-165" style="font-size: 70.7%; font-family: MathJax_Math-italic;">A</span></span></span></span></span></span></span></span></nobr><span class="MJX_Assistive_MathML" role="presentation"><math xmlns="http://www.w3.org/1998/Math/MathML"><mi>P</mi><mo>=</mo><mfrac><mi>F</mi><mi>A</mi></mfrac></math></span></span>
	<script id="MathJax-Element-13" type="math/tex">P = \frac{F}{A}</script>
	 হিসাবে প্রকাশ করা হয়।</li>
	<li>বলের মাত্রিক সূত্র হল <span class="MathJax" data-mathml="<math xmlns="http://www.w3.org/1998/Math/MathML"><mo stretchy="false">[</mo><mi>M</mi><mi>L</mi><msup><mi>T</mi><mrow class="MJX-TeXAtom-ORD"><mo>&#x2212;</mo><mn>2</mn></mrow></msup><mo stretchy="false">]</mo></math>" id="MathJax-Element-14-Frame" role="presentation" style="position: relative;" tabindex="0"><nobr aria-hidden="true"><span class="math" id="MathJax-Span-166" style="width: 4.921em; display: inline-block;"><span style="display: inline-block; position: relative; width: 4.043em; height: 0px; font-size: 122%;"><span style="position: absolute; clip: rect(1.232em, 1003.93em, 2.638em, -999.997em); top: -2.222em; left: 0em;"><span class="mrow" id="MathJax-Span-167"><span class="mo" id="MathJax-Span-168" style="font-family: MathJax_Main;">[</span><span class="mi" id="MathJax-Span-169" style="font-family: MathJax_Math-italic;">M</span><span class="mi" id="MathJax-Span-170" style="font-family: MathJax_Math-italic;">L</span><span class="msubsup" id="MathJax-Span-171"><span style="display: inline-block; position: relative; width: 1.759em; height: 0px;"><span style="position: absolute; clip: rect(3.106em, 1000.71em, 4.16em, -999.997em); top: -3.978em; left: 0em;"><span class="mi" id="MathJax-Span-172" style="font-family: MathJax_Math-italic;">T</span></span><span style="position: absolute; top: -4.33em; left: 0.764em;"><span class="texatom" id="MathJax-Span-173"><span class="mrow" id="MathJax-Span-174"><span class="mo" id="MathJax-Span-175" style="font-size: 70.7%; font-family: MathJax_Main;">&minus;</span><span class="mn" id="MathJax-Span-176" style="font-size: 70.7%; font-family: MathJax_Main;">2</span></span></span></span></span></span><span class="mo" id="MathJax-Span-177" style="font-family: MathJax_Main;">]</span></span></span></span></span></nobr><span class="MJX_Assistive_MathML" role="presentation"><math xmlns="http://www.w3.org/1998/Math/MathML"><mo stretchy="false">[</mo><mi>M</mi><mi>L</mi><msup><mi>T</mi><mrow class="MJX-TeXAtom-ORD"><mo>&minus;</mo><mn>2</mn></mrow></msup><mo stretchy="false">]</mo></math></span></span>
	<script id="MathJax-Element-14" type="math/tex">[M L T^{-2}]</script>
	, যা নিউটনের দ্বিতীয় সূত্র থেকে উদ্ভূত (<span class="MathJax" data-mathml="<math xmlns="http://www.w3.org/1998/Math/MathML"><mi>F</mi><mo>=</mo><mi>m</mi><mi>a</mi></math>" id="MathJax-Element-15-Frame" role="presentation" style="position: relative;" tabindex="0"><nobr aria-hidden="true"><span class="math" id="MathJax-Span-178" style="width: 4.335em; display: inline-block;"><span style="display: inline-block; position: relative; width: 3.516em; height: 0px; font-size: 122%;"><span style="position: absolute; clip: rect(1.35em, 1003.52em, 2.403em, -999.997em); top: -2.222em; left: 0em;"><span class="mrow" id="MathJax-Span-179"><span class="mi" id="MathJax-Span-180" style="font-family: MathJax_Math-italic;">F</span><span class="mo" id="MathJax-Span-181" style="font-family: MathJax_Main; padding-left: 0.296em;">=</span><span class="mi" id="MathJax-Span-182" style="font-family: MathJax_Math-italic; padding-left: 0.296em;">m</span><span class="mi" id="MathJax-Span-183" style="font-family: MathJax_Math-italic;">a</span></span></span></span></span></nobr><span class="MJX_Assistive_MathML" role="presentation"><math xmlns="http://www.w3.org/1998/Math/MathML"><mi>F</mi><mo>=</mo><mi>m</mi><mi>a</mi></math></span></span>
	<script id="MathJax-Element-15" type="math/tex">F = ma</script>
	)।</li>
	<li>ক্ষেত্রফলের মাত্রিক সূত্র হল <span class="MathJax" data-mathml="<math xmlns="http://www.w3.org/1998/Math/MathML"><mo stretchy="false">[</mo><msup><mi>L</mi><mn>2</mn></msup><mo stretchy="false">]</mo></math>" id="MathJax-Element-16-Frame" role="presentation" style="position: relative;" tabindex="0"><nobr aria-hidden="true"><span class="math" id="MathJax-Span-184" style="width: 2.111em; display: inline-block;"><span style="display: inline-block; position: relative; width: 1.701em; height: 0px; font-size: 122%;"><span style="position: absolute; clip: rect(1.232em, 1001.58em, 2.638em, -999.997em); top: -2.222em; left: 0em;"><span class="mrow" id="MathJax-Span-185"><span class="mo" id="MathJax-Span-186" style="font-family: MathJax_Main;">[</span><span class="msubsup" id="MathJax-Span-187"><span style="display: inline-block; position: relative; width: 1.115em; height: 0px;"><span style="position: absolute; clip: rect(3.106em, 1000.65em, 4.16em, -999.997em); top: -3.978em; left: 0em;"><span class="mi" id="MathJax-Span-188" style="font-family: MathJax_Math-italic;">L</span></span><span style="position: absolute; top: -4.33em; left: 0.706em;"><span class="mn" id="MathJax-Span-189" style="font-size: 70.7%; font-family: MathJax_Main;">2</span></span></span></span><span class="mo" id="MathJax-Span-190" style="font-family: MathJax_Main;">]</span></span></span></span></span></nobr><span class="MJX_Assistive_MathML" role="presentation"><math xmlns="http://www.w3.org/1998/Math/MathML"><mo stretchy="false">[</mo><msup><mi>L</mi><mn>2</mn></msup><mo stretchy="false">]</mo></math></span></span>
	<script id="MathJax-Element-16" type="math/tex">[L^2]</script>
	, কারণ এটি একটি দ্বি-মাত্রিক রাশি (<span class="MathJax" data-mathml="<math xmlns="http://www.w3.org/1998/Math/MathML"><mi>L</mi><mo>&#x00D7;</mo><mi>L</mi></math>" id="MathJax-Element-17-Frame" role="presentation" style="position: relative;" tabindex="0"><nobr aria-hidden="true"><span class="math" id="MathJax-Span-191" style="width: 3.223em; display: inline-block;"><span style="display: inline-block; position: relative; width: 2.638em; height: 0px; font-size: 122%;"><span style="position: absolute; clip: rect(1.35em, 1002.58em, 2.403em, -999.997em); top: -2.222em; left: 0em;"><span class="mrow" id="MathJax-Span-192"><span class="mi" id="MathJax-Span-193" style="font-family: MathJax_Math-italic;">L</span><span class="mo" id="MathJax-Span-194" style="font-family: MathJax_Main; padding-left: 0.237em;">x</span><span class="mi" id="MathJax-Span-195" style="font-family: MathJax_Math-italic; padding-left: 0.237em;">L</span></span></span></span></span></nobr><span class="MJX_Assistive_MathML" role="presentation"><math xmlns="http://www.w3.org/1998/Math/MathML"><mi>L</mi><mo>x</mo><mi>L</mi></math></span></span>
	<script id="MathJax-Element-17" type="math/tex">L \times L</script>
	)।</li>
	<li>ক্ষেত্রফল দ্বারা বলের মাত্রিক সূত্রকে ভাগ করলে চাপের মাত্রিক সূত্র পাওয়া যায়: <span class="MathJax" data-mathml="<math xmlns="http://www.w3.org/1998/Math/MathML"><mo stretchy="false">[</mo><mi>M</mi><msup><mi>L</mi><mrow class="MJX-TeXAtom-ORD"><mo>&#x2212;</mo><mn>1</mn></mrow></msup><msup><mi>T</mi><mrow class="MJX-TeXAtom-ORD"><mo>&#x2212;</mo><mn>2</mn></mrow></msup><mo stretchy="false">]</mo></math>" id="MathJax-Element-18-Frame" role="presentation" style="position: relative;" tabindex="0"><nobr aria-hidden="true"><span class="math" id="MathJax-Span-196" style="width: 6.092em; display: inline-block;"><span style="display: inline-block; position: relative; width: 4.98em; height: 0px; font-size: 122%;"><span style="position: absolute; clip: rect(1.232em, 1004.86em, 2.638em, -999.997em); top: -2.222em; left: 0em;"><span class="mrow" id="MathJax-Span-197"><span class="mo" id="MathJax-Span-198" style="font-family: MathJax_Main;">[</span><span class="mi" id="MathJax-Span-199" style="font-family: MathJax_Math-italic;">M</span><span class="msubsup" id="MathJax-Span-200"><span style="display: inline-block; position: relative; width: 1.642em; height: 0px;"><span style="position: absolute; clip: rect(3.106em, 1000.65em, 4.16em, -999.997em); top: -3.978em; left: 0em;"><span class="mi" id="MathJax-Span-201" style="font-family: MathJax_Math-italic;">L</span></span><span style="position: absolute; top: -4.33em; left: 0.706em;"><span class="texatom" id="MathJax-Span-202"><span class="mrow" id="MathJax-Span-203"><span class="mo" id="MathJax-Span-204" style="font-size: 70.7%; font-family: MathJax_Main;">&minus;</span><span class="mn" id="MathJax-Span-205" style="font-size: 70.7%; font-family: MathJax_Main;">1</span></span></span></span></span></span><span class="msubsup" id="MathJax-Span-206"><span style="display: inline-block; position: relative; width: 1.759em; height: 0px;"><span style="position: absolute; clip: rect(3.106em, 1000.71em, 4.16em, -999.997em); top: -3.978em; left: 0em;"><span class="mi" id="MathJax-Span-207" style="font-family: MathJax_Math-italic;">T</span></span><span style="position: absolute; top: -4.33em; left: 0.764em;"><span class="texatom" id="MathJax-Span-208"><span class="mrow" id="MathJax-Span-209"><span class="mo" id="MathJax-Span-210" style="font-size: 70.7%; font-family: MathJax_Main;">&minus;</span><span class="mn" id="MathJax-Span-211" style="font-size: 70.7%; font-family: MathJax_Main;">2</span></span></span></span></span></span><span class="mo" id="MathJax-Span-212" style="font-family: MathJax_Main;">]</span></span></span></span></span></nobr><span class="MJX_Assistive_MathML" role="presentation"><math xmlns="http://www.w3.org/1998/Math/MathML"><mo stretchy="false">[</mo><mi>M</mi><msup><mi>L</mi><mrow class="MJX-TeXAtom-ORD"><mo>&minus;</mo><mn>1</mn></mrow></msup><msup><mi>T</mi><mrow class="MJX-TeXAtom-ORD"><mo>&minus;</mo><mn>2</mn></mrow></msup><mo stretchy="false">]</mo></math></span></span>
	<script id="MathJax-Element-18" type="math/tex">[M L^{-1} T^{-2}]</script>
	।</li>
	<li>সুতরাং, চাপের জন্য সঠিক মাত্রিক সূত্র হল <span class="MathJax" data-mathml="<math xmlns="http://www.w3.org/1998/Math/MathML"><mo stretchy="false">[</mo><mi>M</mi><msup><mi>L</mi><mrow class="MJX-TeXAtom-ORD"><mo>&#x2212;</mo><mn>1</mn></mrow></msup><msup><mi>T</mi><mrow class="MJX-TeXAtom-ORD"><mo>&#x2212;</mo><mn>2</mn></mrow></msup><mo stretchy="false">]</mo></math>" id="MathJax-Element-19-Frame" role="presentation" style="position: relative;" tabindex="0"><nobr aria-hidden="true"><span class="math" id="MathJax-Span-213" style="width: 6.092em; display: inline-block;"><span style="display: inline-block; position: relative; width: 4.98em; height: 0px; font-size: 122%;"><span style="position: absolute; clip: rect(1.232em, 1004.86em, 2.638em, -999.997em); top: -2.222em; left: 0em;"><span class="mrow" id="MathJax-Span-214"><span class="mo" id="MathJax-Span-215" style="font-family: MathJax_Main;">[</span><span class="mi" id="MathJax-Span-216" style="font-family: MathJax_Math-italic;">M</span><span class="msubsup" id="MathJax-Span-217"><span style="display: inline-block; position: relative; width: 1.642em; height: 0px;"><span style="position: absolute; clip: rect(3.106em, 1000.65em, 4.16em, -999.997em); top: -3.978em; left: 0em;"><span class="mi" id="MathJax-Span-218" style="font-family: MathJax_Math-italic;">L</span></span><span style="position: absolute; top: -4.33em; left: 0.706em;"><span class="texatom" id="MathJax-Span-219"><span class="mrow" id="MathJax-Span-220"><span class="mo" id="MathJax-Span-221" style="font-size: 70.7%; font-family: MathJax_Main;">&minus;</span><span class="mn" id="MathJax-Span-222" style="font-size: 70.7%; font-family: MathJax_Main;">1</span></span></span></span></span></span><span class="msubsup" id="MathJax-Span-223"><span style="display: inline-block; position: relative; width: 1.759em; height: 0px;"><span style="position: absolute; clip: rect(3.106em, 1000.71em, 4.16em, -999.997em); top: -3.978em; left: 0em;"><span class="mi" id="MathJax-Span-224" style="font-family: MathJax_Math-italic;">T</span></span><span style="position: absolute; top: -4.33em; left: 0.764em;"><span class="texatom" id="MathJax-Span-225"><span class="mrow" id="MathJax-Span-226"><span class="mo" id="MathJax-Span-227" style="font-size: 70.7%; font-family: MathJax_Main;">&minus;</span><span class="mn" id="MathJax-Span-228" style="font-size: 70.7%; font-family: MathJax_Main;">2</span></span></span></span></span></span><span class="mo" id="MathJax-Span-229" style="font-family: MathJax_Main;">]</span></span></span></span></span></nobr><span class="MJX_Assistive_MathML" role="presentation"><math xmlns="http://www.w3.org/1998/Math/MathML"><mo stretchy="false">[</mo><mi>M</mi><msup><mi>L</mi><mrow class="MJX-TeXAtom-ORD"><mo>&minus;</mo><mn>1</mn></mrow></msup><msup><mi>T</mi><mrow class="MJX-TeXAtom-ORD"><mo>&minus;</mo><mn>2</mn></mrow></msup><mo stretchy="false">]</mo></math></span></span>
	<script id="MathJax-Element-19" type="math/tex">[M L^{-1} T^{-2}]</script>
	।</li>
</ul>

<p><span style="display: flex;gap: 6px;align-items: center;"><img height="26px" src="//cdn.testbook.com/resources/lms_creative_elements/additional-information-image.png" width="26px" /><strong><span style="vertical-align: middle;font-size: 21px;"><u>অতিরিক্ত তথ্য</u></span></strong></span></p>

<ul>
	<li><strong>চাপ:</strong> এটি একটি স্কেলার ভৌত ​​রাশি যা প্রতি একক ক্ষেত্রফলে প্রযুক্ত বলকে উপস্থাপন করে।</li>
	<li><strong>SI একক:</strong> চাপের SI একক হল পাস্কাল (Pa), যেখানে <span class="MathJax" data-mathml="<math xmlns="http://www.w3.org/1998/Math/MathML"><mn>1</mn><mspace width="thinmathspace" /><mtext>Pa</mtext><mo>=</mo><mn>1</mn><mspace width="thinmathspace" /><msup><mtext>N/m</mtext><mn>2</mn></msup></math>" id="MathJax-Element-20-Frame" role="presentation" style="position: relative;" tabindex="0"><nobr aria-hidden="true"><span class="math" id="MathJax-Span-230" style="width: 7.907em; display: inline-block;"><span style="display: inline-block; position: relative; width: 6.443em; height: 0px; font-size: 122%;"><span style="position: absolute; clip: rect(1.115em, 1006.44em, 2.638em, -999.997em); top: -2.222em; left: 0em;"><span class="mrow" id="MathJax-Span-231"><span class="mn" id="MathJax-Span-232" style="font-family: MathJax_Main;">1</span><span class="mtext" id="MathJax-Span-234" style="font-family: MathJax_Main;">Pa</span><span class="mo" id="MathJax-Span-235" style="font-family: MathJax_Main; padding-left: 0.296em;">=</span><span class="mn" id="MathJax-Span-236" style="font-family: MathJax_Main; padding-left: 0.296em;">1</span><span class="msubsup" id="MathJax-Span-238"><span style="display: inline-block; position: relative; width: 2.52em; height: 0px;"><span style="position: absolute; clip: rect(3.047em, 1002.05em, 4.394em, -999.997em); top: -3.978em; left: 0em;"><span class="mtext" id="MathJax-Span-239" style="font-family: MathJax_Main;">N/m</span></span><span style="position: absolute; top: -4.447em; left: 2.111em;"><span class="mn" id="MathJax-Span-240" style="font-size: 70.7%; font-family: MathJax_Main;">2</span></span></span></span></span></span></span></span></nobr><span class="MJX_Assistive_MathML" role="presentation"><math xmlns="http://www.w3.org/1998/Math/MathML"><mn>1</mn><mspace width="thinmathspace"></mspace><mtext>Pa</mtext><mo>=</mo><mn>1</mn><mspace width="thinmathspace"></mspace><msup><mtext>N/m</mtext><mn>2</mn></msup></math></span></span>
	<script id="MathJax-Element-20" type="math/tex">1 \, \text{Pa} = 1 \, \text{N/m}^2</script>
	।</li>
	<li><strong>বায়ুমণ্ডলীয় চাপ:</strong> পৃথিবীর বায়ুমণ্ডল দ্বারা প্রয়োগ করা চাপ প্রায় <span class="MathJax" data-mathml="<math xmlns="http://www.w3.org/1998/Math/MathML"><mn>101</mn><mo>,</mo><mn>325</mn><mspace width="thinmathspace" /><mtext>Pa</mtext></math>" id="MathJax-Element-21-Frame" role="presentation" style="position: relative;" tabindex="0"><nobr aria-hidden="true"><span class="math" id="MathJax-Span-241" style="width: 5.858em; display: inline-block;"><span style="display: inline-block; position: relative; width: 4.804em; height: 0px; font-size: 122%;"><span style="position: absolute; clip: rect(1.35em, 1004.8em, 2.579em, -999.997em); top: -2.222em; left: 0em;"><span class="mrow" id="MathJax-Span-242"><span class="mn" id="MathJax-Span-243" style="font-family: MathJax_Main;">101</span><span class="mo" id="MathJax-Span-244" style="font-family: MathJax_Main;">,</span><span class="mn" id="MathJax-Span-245" style="font-family: MathJax_Main; padding-left: 0.179em;">325</span><span class="mtext" id="MathJax-Span-247" style="font-family: MathJax_Main;">Pa</span></span></span></span></span></nobr><span class="MJX_Assistive_MathML" role="presentation"><math xmlns="http://www.w3.org/1998/Math/MathML"><mn>101</mn><mo>,</mo><mn>325</mn><mspace width="thinmathspace"></mspace><mtext>Pa</mtext></math></span></span>
	<script id="MathJax-Element-21" type="math/tex">101,325 \, \text{Pa}</script>
	(1 atm)।</li>
	<li><strong>চাপের প্রকারভেদ:</strong> রেফারেন্স পয়েন্টের উপর ভিত্তি করে পরম চাপ, গেজ চাপ এবং ডিফারেনশিয়াল চাপ হল সাধারণ শ্রেণিবিন্যাস।</li>
	<li><strong>চাপের প্রয়োগ:</strong> আবহাওয়া, প্রকৌশল (যেমন, হাইড্রোলিক্স), এবং চিকিৎসা (যেমন, রক্তচাপ পর্যবেক্ষণ) এর মতো ক্ষেত্রগুলিতে চাপ পরিমাপ অত্যন্ত গুরুত্বপূর্ণ।</li>
</ul>

&lt;p data-end=&quot;57&quot; data-start=&quot;0&quot;&gt;The correct answer is &lt;u&gt;&lt;strong&gt;They release OH- ions in water.&lt;/strong&gt;&lt;/u&gt;.&lt;/p&gt;

&lt;p data-end=&quot;57&quot; data-start=&quot;0&quot;&gt;&lt;span style=&quot;display: flex;gap: 6px;align-items: center;&quot;&gt;&lt;img height=&quot;26px&quot; src=&quot;//cdn.testbook.com/resources/lms_creative_elements/key-point-image.png&quot; width=&quot;26px&quot; /&gt;&lt;strong&gt;&lt;span style=&quot;vertical-align: middle;font-size: 21px;&quot;&gt;&lt;u&gt;Key Points&lt;/u&gt;&lt;/span&gt;&lt;/strong&gt;&lt;/span&gt;&lt;/p&gt;

&lt;ul&gt;
	&lt;li data-end=&quot;284&quot; data-start=&quot;78&quot;&gt;&lt;strong&gt;Acids&lt;/strong&gt; are chemical substances that exhibit specific characteristics when dissolved in water.&lt;/li&gt;
	&lt;li data-end=&quot;605&quot; data-start=&quot;482&quot;&gt;They &lt;strong&gt;turn blue litmus paper red&lt;/strong&gt;, which is a common test to identify acidic substances. &lt;em&gt;&lt;span style=&quot;font-weight: bolder;&quot;&gt;This statement is correct.&lt;/span&gt;&lt;/em&gt;&lt;/li&gt;
	&lt;li data-end=&quot;692&quot; data-start=&quot;610&quot;&gt;Acids generally have a &lt;strong&gt;sour taste&lt;/strong&gt;. For example, lemon juice contains citric acid, which tastes sour. &lt;em&gt;&lt;span style=&quot;font-weight: bolder;&quot;&gt;This statement is correct.&lt;/span&gt;&lt;/em&gt;&lt;/li&gt;
	&lt;li data-end=&quot;1041&quot; data-start=&quot;850&quot;&gt;Acids react with bases to form &lt;strong&gt;salt and water&lt;/strong&gt;. This reaction is called &lt;strong&gt;neutralization&lt;/strong&gt;. &lt;em&gt;&lt;span style=&quot;font-weight: bolder;&quot;&gt;This statement is correct.&lt;/span&gt;&lt;/em&gt;&lt;/li&gt;
	&lt;li data-end=&quot;1162&quot; data-start=&quot;1046&quot;&gt;Acids release &lt;strong&gt;H⁺ ions&lt;/strong&gt; (protons) when dissolved in water, not OH⁻ ions. The release of OH⁻ ions is a characteristic property of bases. &lt;em&gt;&lt;span style=&quot;font-weight: bolder;&quot;&gt;Hence, this statement is incorrect and is the correct answer.&lt;/span&gt;&lt;/em&gt;&lt;/li&gt;
&lt;/ul&gt;

&lt;p&gt;&lt;span style=&quot;display: flex;gap: 6px;align-items: center;&quot;&gt;&lt;img height=&quot;26px&quot; src=&quot;//cdn.testbook.com/resources/lms_creative_elements/additional-information-image.png&quot; width=&quot;26px&quot; /&gt;&lt;strong&gt;&lt;span style=&quot;vertical-align: middle;font-size: 21px;&quot;&gt;&lt;u&gt;Additional Information&lt;/u&gt;&lt;/span&gt;&lt;/strong&gt;&lt;/span&gt;&lt;/p&gt;

&lt;ul&gt;
	&lt;li&gt;&lt;strong&gt;Characteristics of Acids:&lt;/strong&gt;

	&lt;ul&gt;
		&lt;li&gt;Acids are substances that produce &lt;strong&gt;hydrogen ions (H⁺)&lt;/strong&gt; when dissolved in water. For example, hydrochloric acid (HCl) dissociates into H⁺ and Cl⁻ in water.&lt;/li&gt;
		&lt;li&gt;They have a &lt;strong&gt;sour taste&lt;/strong&gt; (e.g., vinegar contains acetic acid, and lemon contains citric acid).&lt;/li&gt;
		&lt;li&gt;Acids react with metals to release &lt;strong&gt;hydrogen gas&lt;/strong&gt;. For instance, hydrochloric acid reacts with zinc to produce hydrogen gas.&lt;/li&gt;
		&lt;li&gt;They change the color of indicators: &lt;strong&gt;Blue litmus paper turns red&lt;/strong&gt; in the presence of acids.&lt;/li&gt;
		&lt;li&gt;Acids react with carbonates and bicarbonates to produce &lt;strong&gt;carbon dioxide gas&lt;/strong&gt;.&lt;/li&gt;
	&lt;/ul&gt;
	&lt;/li&gt;
	&lt;li&gt;&lt;strong&gt;Differences Between Acids and Bases:&lt;/strong&gt;
	&lt;ul&gt;
		&lt;li&gt;&lt;strong&gt;Acids:&lt;/strong&gt; Produce H⁺ ions, taste sour, turn blue litmus paper red, and have a pH below 7.&lt;/li&gt;
		&lt;li&gt;&lt;strong&gt;Bases:&lt;/strong&gt; Produce OH⁻ ions, taste bitter, feel slippery, turn red litmus paper blue, and have a pH above 7.&lt;/li&gt;
	&lt;/ul&gt;
	&lt;/li&gt;
	&lt;li&gt;&lt;strong&gt;Examples of Acids and Bases:&lt;/strong&gt;
	&lt;ul&gt;
		&lt;li&gt;&lt;strong&gt;Acids:&lt;/strong&gt; Hydrochloric acid (HCl), Sulfuric acid (H₂SO₄), Nitric acid (HNO₃), Acetic acid (CH₃COOH).&lt;/li&gt;
		&lt;li&gt;&lt;strong&gt;Bases:&lt;/strong&gt; Sodium hydroxide (NaOH), Potassium hydroxide (KOH), Calcium hydroxide (Ca(OH)₂), Ammonium hydroxide (NH₄OH).&lt;/li&gt;
	&lt;/ul&gt;
	&lt;/li&gt;
&lt;/ul&gt;

&lt;p&gt;&lt;span style=&quot;display: flex;gap: 6px;align-items: center;&quot;&gt;&lt;img height=&quot;26px&quot; src=&quot;//cdn.testbook.com/resources/lms_creative_elements/important-point-image.png&quot; width=&quot;26px&quot; /&gt;&lt;strong&gt;&lt;span style=&quot;vertical-align: middle;font-size: 21px;&quot;&gt;&lt;u&gt;Important Points&lt;/u&gt;&lt;/span&gt;&lt;/strong&gt;&lt;/span&gt;&lt;/p&gt;

&lt;ul&gt;
	&lt;li&gt;&lt;strong&gt;pH Scale:&lt;/strong&gt;

	&lt;ul&gt;
		&lt;li&gt;The &lt;strong&gt;pH scale&lt;/strong&gt; ranges from 0 to 14 and measures the acidity or alkalinity of a solution.&lt;/li&gt;
		&lt;li&gt;A pH less than 7 indicates acidity, while a pH greater than 7 indicates alkalinity.&lt;/li&gt;
		&lt;li&gt;A pH of exactly 7 is considered neutral, as seen in pure water.&lt;/li&gt;
	&lt;/ul&gt;
	&lt;/li&gt;
	&lt;li&gt;&lt;strong&gt;Neutralization Reaction:&lt;/strong&gt;
	&lt;ul&gt;
		&lt;li&gt;When an acid reacts with a base, it forms salt and water in a process called &lt;strong&gt;neutralization&lt;/strong&gt;.&lt;/li&gt;
		&lt;li&gt;Example: HCl + NaOH &amp;rarr; NaCl + H₂O (hydrochloric acid reacts with sodium hydroxide to form sodium chloride and water).&lt;/li&gt;
	&lt;/ul&gt;
	&lt;/li&gt;
	&lt;li&gt;&lt;strong&gt;Applications of Acids and Bases:&lt;/strong&gt;
	&lt;ul&gt;
		&lt;li&gt;&lt;strong&gt;Acids:&lt;/strong&gt; Used in cleaning agents (e.g., hydrochloric acid), food preservation (e.g., vinegar), and production of fertilizers (e.g., sulfuric acid).&lt;/li&gt;
		&lt;li&gt;&lt;strong&gt;Bases:&lt;/strong&gt; Used in soap making (e.g., sodium hydroxide), antacids (e.g., magnesium hydroxide), and cleaning agents (e.g., ammonia).&lt;/li&gt;
	&lt;/ul&gt;
	&lt;/li&gt;
&lt;/ul&gt;

&lt;p&gt;The correct answer is &lt;u&gt;&lt;strong&gt;Density&lt;/strong&gt;&lt;/u&gt;.&lt;/p&gt;

&lt;p&gt;&lt;span style=&quot;display: flex;gap: 6px;align-items: center;&quot;&gt;&lt;img height=&quot;26px&quot; src=&quot;//cdn.testbook.com/resources/lms_creative_elements/key-point-image.png&quot; width=&quot;26px&quot; /&gt;&lt;strong&gt;&lt;span style=&quot;vertical-align: middle;font-size: 21px;&quot;&gt;&lt;u&gt;Key Points&lt;/u&gt;&lt;/span&gt;&lt;/strong&gt;&lt;/span&gt;&lt;/p&gt;

&lt;ul style=&quot;color: (33, 37, 41);&quot;&gt;
	&lt;li&gt;&lt;strong&gt;Density&lt;/strong&gt; is defined as the &lt;strong&gt;mass per unit volume&lt;/strong&gt; of a substance.&lt;/li&gt;
	&lt;li&gt;It is mathematically expressed as &lt;strong&gt;Density = Mass/Volume&lt;/strong&gt;.&lt;/li&gt;
	&lt;li&gt;The dimensional formula for mass is &lt;strong&gt;[M]&lt;/strong&gt;, and for volume, it is &lt;strong&gt;[L&amp;sup3;]&lt;/strong&gt;.&lt;/li&gt;
	&lt;li&gt;Thus, the dimensional formula for density is &lt;strong&gt;[M L⁻&amp;sup3;]&lt;/strong&gt;.&lt;/li&gt;
	&lt;li&gt;This dimensional formula indicates that density has one unit of &lt;strong&gt;mass (M)&lt;/strong&gt; and is inversely proportional to the cube of the length (L).&lt;/li&gt;
	&lt;li&gt;Density is an important physical quantity used in various fields such as &lt;strong&gt;fluid mechanics, material science, and engineering applications&lt;/strong&gt;.&lt;/li&gt;
	&lt;li&gt;Examples of density include the density of water as &lt;strong&gt;1000 kg/m&amp;sup3;&lt;/strong&gt; and the density of air as approximately &lt;strong&gt;1.225 kg/m&amp;sup3; at sea level&lt;/strong&gt;.&lt;/li&gt;
&lt;/ul&gt;

&lt;p&gt;&lt;span style=&quot;display: flex;gap: 6px;align-items: center;&quot;&gt;&lt;img height=&quot;26px&quot; src=&quot;//cdn.testbook.com/resources/lms_creative_elements/additional-information-image.png&quot; width=&quot;26px&quot; /&gt;&amp;nbsp;&lt;strong&gt;&lt;span style=&quot;vertical-align: middle;font-size: 21px;&quot;&gt;&lt;u&gt;Additional Information&lt;/u&gt;&lt;/span&gt;&lt;/strong&gt;&lt;/span&gt;&lt;/p&gt;

&lt;ul&gt;
	&lt;li&gt;&lt;u&gt;&lt;strong&gt;Pressure&lt;/strong&gt;&lt;/u&gt;

	&lt;ul&gt;
		&lt;li&gt;&lt;strong&gt;Pressure&lt;/strong&gt; is defined as the &lt;strong&gt;force applied per unit area&lt;/strong&gt;.&lt;/li&gt;
		&lt;li&gt;Its dimensional formula is &lt;strong&gt;[M L⁻&amp;sup1; T⁻&amp;sup2;]&lt;/strong&gt;, which is different from density.&lt;/li&gt;
		&lt;li&gt;Pressure is measured in units such as &lt;strong&gt;Pascals (Pa)&lt;/strong&gt; in the SI system.&lt;/li&gt;
		&lt;li&gt;Applications of pressure include &lt;strong&gt;hydraulics, pneumatics, and weather prediction&lt;/strong&gt;.&lt;/li&gt;
	&lt;/ul&gt;
	&lt;/li&gt;
	&lt;li&gt;&lt;u&gt;&lt;strong&gt;Work&lt;/strong&gt;&lt;/u&gt;
	&lt;ul&gt;
		&lt;li&gt;&lt;strong&gt;Work&lt;/strong&gt; is defined as the product of &lt;strong&gt;force and displacement in the direction of the force&lt;/strong&gt;.&lt;/li&gt;
		&lt;li&gt;Its dimensional formula is &lt;strong&gt;[M L&amp;sup2; T⁻&amp;sup2;]&lt;/strong&gt;.&lt;/li&gt;
		&lt;li&gt;Work is measured in &lt;strong&gt;Joules (J)&lt;/strong&gt; in the SI system.&lt;/li&gt;
		&lt;li&gt;It is widely used in physics and engineering to analyze energy transfer.&lt;/li&gt;
	&lt;/ul&gt;
	&lt;/li&gt;
	&lt;li&gt;&lt;u&gt;&lt;strong&gt;Energy&lt;/strong&gt;&lt;/u&gt;
	&lt;ul&gt;
		&lt;li&gt;&lt;strong&gt;Energy&lt;/strong&gt; is the capacity to perform work.&lt;/li&gt;
		&lt;li&gt;Its dimensional formula is the same as that of work, &lt;strong&gt;[M L&amp;sup2; T⁻&amp;sup2;]&lt;/strong&gt;.&lt;/li&gt;
		&lt;li&gt;Energy is measured in &lt;strong&gt;Joules (J)&lt;/strong&gt; in the SI system.&lt;/li&gt;
		&lt;li&gt;Examples include &lt;strong&gt;kinetic energy, potential energy, and thermal energy&lt;/strong&gt;.&lt;/li&gt;
	&lt;/ul&gt;
	&lt;/li&gt;
&lt;/ul&gt;

&lt;p&gt;The Correct answer is &lt;u&gt;&lt;strong&gt;Hydrogen bonding&lt;/strong&gt;&lt;/u&gt;.&lt;/p&gt;

&lt;p&gt;&lt;span style=&quot;display: flex;gap: 6px;align-items: center;&quot;&gt;&lt;img height=&quot;26px&quot; src=&quot;//cdn.testbook.com/resources/lms_creative_elements/key-point-image.png&quot; width=&quot;26px&quot; /&gt;&lt;strong&gt;&lt;span style=&quot;vertical-align: middle;font-size: 21px;&quot;&gt;&lt;u&gt;Key Points&lt;/u&gt;&lt;/span&gt;&lt;/strong&gt;&lt;/span&gt;&lt;/p&gt;

&lt;ul style=&quot;color: (33, 37, 41);&quot;&gt;
	&lt;li&gt;In &lt;strong&gt;DNA&lt;/strong&gt;, the two complementary strands are held together by &lt;strong&gt;hydrogen bonds&lt;/strong&gt; between the nitrogenous bases.&lt;/li&gt;
	&lt;li&gt;&lt;strong&gt;Adenine (A)&lt;/strong&gt; always pairs with &lt;strong&gt;Thymine (T)&lt;/strong&gt; through two hydrogen bonds, while &lt;strong&gt;Guanine (G)&lt;/strong&gt; pairs with &lt;strong&gt;Cytosine (C)&lt;/strong&gt; using three hydrogen bonds.&lt;/li&gt;
	&lt;li&gt;This specific pairing is known as &lt;strong&gt;complementary base pairing&lt;/strong&gt;, which is essential for the accurate replication of genetic material.&lt;/li&gt;
	&lt;li&gt;&lt;strong&gt;Hydrogen bonds&lt;/strong&gt; are weak, non-covalent interactions that allow the double helix structure of DNA to unzip during replication and transcription.&lt;/li&gt;
	&lt;li&gt;Although individually weak, the cumulative effect of a large number of hydrogen bonds provides structural &lt;strong&gt;stability&lt;/strong&gt; to the DNA double helix.&lt;/li&gt;
	&lt;li&gt;The double helix model of DNA was first proposed by &lt;strong&gt;James Watson&lt;/strong&gt; and &lt;strong&gt;Francis Crick&lt;/strong&gt;, and their discovery highlighted the role of hydrogen bonding in maintaining DNA&amp;rsquo;s structural integrity.&lt;/li&gt;
	&lt;li&gt;These bonds ensure that mutations are minimized by enabling &lt;strong&gt;specificity&lt;/strong&gt; in base pairing during DNA replication.&lt;/li&gt;
	&lt;li&gt;Hydrogen bonding occurs due to the difference in &lt;strong&gt;electronegativity&lt;/strong&gt; between the hydrogen atom and the electronegative atoms (e.g., oxygen or nitrogen) involved in the base pairs.&lt;/li&gt;
&lt;/ul&gt;

&lt;p&gt;&lt;span style=&quot;display: flex;gap: 6px;align-items: center;&quot;&gt;&lt;img height=&quot;26px&quot; src=&quot;//cdn.testbook.com/resources/lms_creative_elements/additional-information-image.png&quot; width=&quot;26px&quot; /&gt;&amp;nbsp;&lt;strong&gt;&lt;span style=&quot;vertical-align: middle;font-size: 21px;&quot;&gt;&lt;u&gt;Additional Information&lt;/u&gt;&lt;/span&gt;&lt;/strong&gt;&lt;/span&gt;&lt;/p&gt;

&lt;ul&gt;
	&lt;li&gt;&lt;u&gt;&lt;strong&gt;Ionic bonding&lt;/strong&gt;&lt;/u&gt;

	&lt;ul&gt;
		&lt;li&gt;&lt;strong&gt;Ionic bonds&lt;/strong&gt; occur due to the electrostatic attraction between oppositely charged ions, which is not relevant in the context of DNA base pairing.&lt;/li&gt;
		&lt;li&gt;Examples of ionic bonding are typically found in compounds like &lt;strong&gt;sodium chloride (NaCl)&lt;/strong&gt;.&lt;/li&gt;
		&lt;li&gt;In DNA, ionic interactions are involved in the stabilization of the double helix through interactions between the negatively charged &lt;strong&gt;phosphate backbone&lt;/strong&gt; and positively charged ions, but they are not responsible for base pairing.&lt;/li&gt;
	&lt;/ul&gt;
	&lt;/li&gt;
	&lt;li&gt;&lt;u&gt;&lt;strong&gt;Van Der Waals interactions&lt;/strong&gt;&lt;/u&gt;
	&lt;ul&gt;
		&lt;li&gt;&lt;strong&gt;Van Der Waals forces&lt;/strong&gt; are weak, short-range forces that arise from fluctuating dipoles, contributing to DNA&amp;rsquo;s overall structural stability.&lt;/li&gt;
		&lt;li&gt;These interactions are present between stacked bases in the DNA double helix, known as &lt;strong&gt;base stacking interactions&lt;/strong&gt;, but they do not play a direct role in base pairing.&lt;/li&gt;
	&lt;/ul&gt;
	&lt;/li&gt;
	&lt;li&gt;&lt;u&gt;&lt;strong&gt;Covalent bonding&lt;/strong&gt;&lt;/u&gt;
	&lt;ul&gt;
		&lt;li&gt;&lt;strong&gt;Covalent bonds&lt;/strong&gt; involve the sharing of electron pairs between atoms, and they are responsible for the formation of the &lt;strong&gt;sugar-phosphate backbone&lt;/strong&gt; in DNA.&lt;/li&gt;
		&lt;li&gt;These bonds are much stronger than hydrogen bonds and provide the primary structure of DNA, but they do not mediate base pairing.&lt;/li&gt;
	&lt;/ul&gt;
	&lt;/li&gt;
&lt;/ul&gt;

&lt;p&gt;The correct answer is &lt;u&gt;&lt;strong&gt;Support of guard cells in stomatal function&lt;/strong&gt;&lt;/u&gt;.&lt;/p&gt;

&lt;p&gt;&lt;span style=&quot;display: flex;gap: 6px;align-items: center;&quot;&gt;&lt;img height=&quot;26px&quot; src=&quot;//cdn.testbook.com/resources/lms_creative_elements/key-point-image.png&quot; width=&quot;26px&quot; /&gt;&lt;u style=&quot;font-size: 21px; font-weight: bolder; font-family: var(--bs-body-font-family); text-align: var(--bs-body-text-align);&quot;&gt;Key Points&lt;/u&gt;&lt;/span&gt;&lt;/p&gt;

&lt;ul&gt;
	&lt;li&gt;Subsidiary cells are specialized epidermal cells that are associated with guard cells and help in stomatal function.&lt;/li&gt;
	&lt;li&gt;They play an indirect role in regulating the opening and closing of stomata by providing mechanical support to guard cells.&lt;/li&gt;
	&lt;li&gt;Subsidiary cells contribute to maintaining the ion balance and turgor pressure required for guard cells to function effectively.&lt;/li&gt;
	&lt;li&gt;These cells are part of the stomatal complex, which is crucial for gas exchange and transpiration in plants.&lt;/li&gt;
	&lt;li&gt;The presence of subsidiary cells varies among plant species and is a characteristic feature used for plant identification.&lt;/li&gt;
&lt;/ul&gt;

&lt;p&gt;&lt;span style=&quot;display: flex;gap: 6px;align-items: center;&quot;&gt;&lt;img height=&quot;26px&quot; src=&quot;//cdn.testbook.com/resources/lms_creative_elements/additional-information-image.png&quot; width=&quot;26px&quot; /&gt;&lt;strong&gt;&lt;span style=&quot;vertical-align: middle;font-size: 21px;&quot;&gt;&lt;u&gt;Additional Information&lt;/u&gt;&lt;/span&gt;&lt;/strong&gt;&lt;/span&gt;&lt;/p&gt;

&lt;ul&gt;
	&lt;li&gt;&lt;strong&gt;Stomata:&lt;/strong&gt;

	&lt;ul&gt;
		&lt;li&gt;Stomata are microscopic pores present on the surface of leaves and stems that facilitate gas exchange (CO2 intake and O2 release).&lt;/li&gt;
		&lt;li&gt;They are surrounded by guard cells, which regulate their opening and closing based on environmental conditions.&lt;/li&gt;
	&lt;/ul&gt;
	&lt;/li&gt;
	&lt;li&gt;&lt;strong&gt;Guard Cells:&lt;/strong&gt;
	&lt;ul&gt;
		&lt;li&gt;Guard cells are specialized cells that control the size of the stomatal pore by changing their shape.&lt;/li&gt;
		&lt;li&gt;They respond to factors like light, water availability, and internal CO2 concentration.&lt;/li&gt;
	&lt;/ul&gt;
	&lt;/li&gt;
	&lt;li&gt;&lt;strong&gt;Subsidiary Cells:&lt;/strong&gt;
	&lt;ul&gt;
		&lt;li&gt;Subsidiary cells are part of the epidermis and surround guard cells, forming the stomatal complex.&lt;/li&gt;
		&lt;li&gt;They vary in shape, size, and arrangement depending on the plant species.&lt;/li&gt;
	&lt;/ul&gt;
	&lt;/li&gt;
	&lt;li&gt;&lt;strong&gt;Function of Stomatal Complex:&lt;/strong&gt;
	&lt;ul&gt;
		&lt;li&gt;Facilitates transpiration and cooling of the plant.&lt;/li&gt;
		&lt;li&gt;Plays a key role in photosynthesis by enabling CO2 uptake.&lt;/li&gt;
		&lt;li&gt;Helps maintain the plant&amp;#39;s water balance by regulating water loss.&lt;/li&gt;
	&lt;/ul&gt;
	&lt;/li&gt;
&lt;/ul&gt;
